    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Chapter 6, P14. Consider three LANs interconnected by two routers, as shown in Figure 6.33. ",
        "bbox": [
            168,
            391,
            600,
            402
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "a Assign IP addresses to all of the interfaces. For Subnet 1 use addresses of the form 192.168.1.xxx; for Subnet 2 uses addresses of the form 192.168.2.xxx; and for Subnet 3 use addresses of the form 192.168.3.xxx. ",
        "bbox": [
            168,
            403,
            818,
            425
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "b Assign MAC addresses to all of the adapters. ",
        "bbox": [
            168,
            427,
            386,
            437
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "c Consider sending an IP datagram from Host E to Host B. Suppose all of the ARP tables are up to date. Enumerate all the steps, as done for the single-router example in Section 6.4.1. ",
        "bbox": [
            166,
            439,
            820,
            461
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "d Repeat (c), now assuming that the ARP table in the sending host is empty (and the other tables are up to date). ",
        "bbox": [
            168,
            463,
            690,
            473
        ],
        "page_idx": 3
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "a、与b如图",
        "bbox": [
